    <name>
				<text>13.5.4.2 T  Integrate Partial Fractions</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Express \(\displaystyle {@exp2@}\) as the sum of its partial fractions and hence find \(\displaystyle\int {@exp2@}\ \mathrm{d}x\).</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>
        <p>First write \(\displaystyle {@exp2@}\) in the form \(\dfrac{A}{x-{@a1@}} + \dfrac{B}{x+{@b1@}}\). </p>
        <p> \(A =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] and \(B =\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>Then \(\displaystyle\int {@exp2@}\ \mathrm{d}x =\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt2]]
        </p>
    </li>

</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<ol class="HELM_parts">
  <li> <p>\(\displaystyle {@exp2@}\) is a proper fraction, therefore the partial fraction decomposition is of the form</p>
    <p>\(\displaystyle {@exp2@} = \dfrac{A}{x-{@a1@}} + \dfrac{B}{x+{@b1@}}\). </p>
    <p>Multiplying both sides by the denominator and equating coefficients yields</p>
    <p> \(\displaystyle {@exp2@} = \displaystyle {@exp1@}\). So \(A = \displaystyle {@taA@}\) and \(B = \displaystyle {@taB@}\).</p>
    
  </li>
  <li>
    <p> \(\begin{aligned} \displaystyle\int {@exp2@} \ \mathrm{d}x &amp;= \displaystyle\int {@exp1@}\ \mathrm{d}x, \\ &amp;= {@ta3@} \end{aligned}\)</p>
    
  </li>
  
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
